{"source_key":"sha256-f88bd5c54ac5fbbfc982c6d403b2565f","record_index":542,"record_hash":"sha256:4b44376a90751d643eb571b5df3ac3935ec3b785f6812d87a7b13ea253a1e5fd","timestamp":"2026-05-24T14:46:05.661Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: a83c21\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1549\nOutput:\n# Agent Trail\n\nAgent Trail is the review-adjacent product surface for captured agent sessions.\nIt is the page a reviewer opens from a pull request to understand the agent work\nbehind a change.\n\n## Working Name\n\nUse **Agent Trail** for now.\n\nGood PR link text:\n\n- View Agent Trail\n- Explore Agent Trail\n- Agent Trail for this PR\n\nAvoid names like \"transcript\", \"audit log\", or \"provenance report\" for the\nproduct surface. The page may contain transcript records and provenance facts,\nbut the user-facing promise is simpler: follow the useful trail behind this\nchange.\n\n## Product Shape\n\nFor v1, a reviewer starts from a GitHub pull request URL and opens the matching\nGitButler-owned Agent Trail URL by replacing the host. The server builds or\nloads a generated snapshot for that public pull request.\n\nExplicit PR description links, bot comments, check-run details links, or GitHub\napp panels can come later as distribution channels. They are not required for\nthe first build.\n\nThe page lets the reviewer explore captured agent context related to the pull\nrequest:\n\n- prompts and requests from the human\n- assistant responses and claims\n- tool calls and tool results\n- tests and validation attempts\n- decisions and tradeoffs\n- follow-up questions\n- edge cases discussed or missed\n\nThis is not primarily a chat transcript viewer. The transcript is the source of\ntruth, but the review experience should be organized around helping a reviewer\nunderstand the change.\n\n## Core Question\n\nAgent Trail should answer:\n\n> What agent context helps me review this pull request?\n\nIt should not claim:\n\n> This agent session authored this pull request.\n\nThe language should stay evidence-based. Say that a session or turn is related\nto a pull request, review, or branch. Do not present related agent data as proof\nof authorship. Change-target lookup can come later, but it is not part of the\nMVP.\n\n## MVP Contract\n\nInput:\n\n```text\nhttps://agent-trail.gi\n[TRUNCATED]\nta may not always include\nreview information. When it is present, it is the strongest first lookup for a\nPR-scoped Agent Trail.\n\nThe server can also use the GitHub API to resolve PR metadata, especially the\nhead branch behind the pull request. The canonical v1 flow is:\n\n```text\nparse PR URL -> GitHub PR lookup -> initialize/refresh repo cache\n-> fetch refs/meta/main -> but-agentlog lookup -> snapshot page\n```\n\nThe server should fetch public PR metadata from GitHub, resolve the PR head\nbranch, and search both useful MVP targets in one pass:\n\n```text\nreview target: gitbutler-review:13936\nbranch target: ref:refs/heads/<pr-head-branch>\n```\n\nCurrent preference: search both when PR metadata is already available, then rank\nreview-target hits above branch-only hits. If GitHub PR lookup fails, v1 should\nfail closed with a retryable error state instead of guessing from GitMeta alone.\n\nBranch fallback is useful but weaker. A branch can be reused, renamed, or shared\nacross unrelated work. The UI should show why each session matched and avoid\ntreating branch-only matches as proof that the session belongs to the PR.\nBranch-only matches should be visually separated from review-target matches and\nraw record drill-down for branch-only matches should require an explicit expand.\n\nChange target lookup is not relevant for the MVP. It can be considered later if\nAgent Trail needs a deeper GitButler-specific view of stacked changes.\n\nThe first version should focus on public/open-source repositories. Private\nrepository access, GitHub OAuth, GitButler workspace access, and explicit share\nlinks can come later.\n\nFor public v1, Agent Trail treats a publicly fetchable `refs/meta/main` as\nalready published metadata. On-demand URL replacement does not grant access to\nprivate data; it only renders a review page from metadata that is fetchable\nwithout credentials.\n\nThis entry point should show one of:\n\n- an existing published trail\n- a newly generated review-safe overview, if access and policy allow it\n- a clear \"no trail available\" state\n\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T14:46:05.661Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}